      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"total_weeks\":12,\"goal_description\":\"Return From Injury — Plantar Fasciitis Recovery & Base Rebuilding\",\"phases\":[{\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":8,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":12,\"intensity_distribution\":\"100% easy, walk breaks as needed\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":372,\"notes\":\"Welcome back, James. These first four weeks are about rebuilding the tissue tolerance in your foot and re-establishing the habit of consistent movement — not fitness gains. Every run is capped at 20 minutes of easy effort (325–372 sec/km range), and you'll use walk breaks any time you feel foot discomfort. Three runs per week, Saturday being your longest. No speedwork. No exceptions, not because we're being cautious for caution's sake, but because plantar fascia tissue adapts slowly and needs progressive load — not a shock to the system. Think of each easy run as a deposit into a long-term account. The payoff comes later. Deload in Week 4: drop back to Week 1 volume.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Build\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":13,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":18,\"intensity_distribution\":\"90% easy / 10% moderate (tempo only if medically cleared)\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":360,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":325,\"notes\":\"By Week 5, assuming your physiotherapist gives the green light to extend duration beyond 20 minutes, we begin gently lengthening your Saturday long run. The other two runs stay easy and controlled. This phase is still primarily aerobic base work — we're building the cardiovascular and musculoskeletal foundation your pre-injury fitness was built on. If foot pain returns at any point, we pause and go back to Phase 1 protocols. Tempo work is listed as a conditional option only — it does not appear in your plan until you are explicitly cleared for speed work. Deload in Week 8.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Peak\",\"weeks\":3,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":19,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":22,\"intensity_distribution\":\"80% easy / 20% moderate\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Tempo\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":345,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":270,\"notes\":\"Weeks 9–11 represent the highest load block of this return plan. Saturday long runs extend meaningfully here, and if you have full physiotherapist clearance for intensity, one mid-week run may include light tempo efforts. That said, this is still a return-from-injury plan — the 'peak' here is modest by design. Your pre-injury pace-zone index of 46.5 tells us your aerobic engine is capable. The goal now is to reconnect your fitness to your body's structural readiness, not to race your former self. Paces remain easy-to-moderate. No repetition or interval work in this block.\",\"includes_deload\":false},{\"phase_type\":\"Recovery\",\"weeks\":1,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":12,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":10,\"intensity_distribution\":\"100% easy\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":372,\"notes\":\"Week 12 is a consolidation week — easy movement, reflection, and preparation for whatever comes next. This is where you assess how your foot has responded to 11 weeks of progressive load, celebrate the consistency it took to get here, and have a conversation with your physiotherapist about the next chapter. A follow-up fitness assessment at this point will help us set a realistic race goal for later in 2026 if that interests you.\",\"includes_deload\":false}],\"rationale\":\"James is returning from active plantar fasciitis with physiotherapist clearance for easy running only, capped at 20 minutes per session, with no speed work authorized. His pre-injury 10K time of 44:00 gives us a pace-zone index of 46.5 — solid intermediate fitness — but his recent training history (2.4 km in one week, climbing to 8.5 km over three weeks) tells us we're starting from a fragile base. The plan is built on three non-negotiables: (1) all easy paces fall within the physiotherapist-approved and Daniels-derived easy range of 5:25–6:12/km (325–372 sec/km); (2) volume increases no more than 10% week-over-week; (3) deload weeks occur at Weeks 4 and 8. The four-phase structure — Base, Build, Peak, Recovery — mirrors standard periodization but is scaled to injury-return realities. Speed work appears only as a conditional option in later phases, and only upon explicit medical clearance. CrossTraining (swimming, cycling, pool running) is encouraged as a complement to running volume, particularly in Phase 1, to maintain cardiovascular fitness without adding foot load. The Saturday long run anchor respects James's stated preference and gives the week a natural rhythm. This plan is not about recapturing 2025 fitness in 12 weeks. It is about building something durable.\",\"warnings\":\"IMPORTANT: This plan is built around your current physiotherapist clearance for 20 minutes of easy running only, with no speed work. Before progressing to Phase 2 (Week 5) or introducing any tempo running in Phase 3, you must obtain explicit clearance from your physiotherapist or a sports medicine professional. If you experience any of the following, stop running and contact your physiotherapist before continuing: sharp or worsening heel/arch pain during or after a run, pain that does not resolve within 24 hours of a session, morning foot pain that is increasing rather than decreasing over time. Do not redistribute missed mileage — if you miss a run, simply move forward with the next scheduled session. This plan assumes no diagnosis or treatment advice from the coach. All medical decisions remain with your healthcare team.\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
